<DocsLayout title="Conducting Research" toc={toc}>

  <h1>Conducting Research</h1>

  <img src="/explorer.png" alt="Conducting Research" style="width: 100%; max-width: 600px; margin: 1.5rem auto; display: block;" />

  <p>
    Every piece of research you do stands on the shoulders of giants — the accumulated work
    of countless researchers who came before you. Your job is not to reinvent the wheel, but
    to understand what has already been built well enough to know where the next step lies.
    This guide will help you navigate the academic publishing ecosystem, find and evaluate
    relevant work, and situate your thesis within the broader literature.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Publication Venues ─────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="venues">Publication Venues</h2>

  <p>
    In computer science and AI, research is primarily disseminated through
    conferences and journals. Understanding the landscape of venues
    helps you judge the significance of a paper and, eventually, where to aim your own work.
  </p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Venue type</th><th>Typical timeline</th><th>What you'll find</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Workshops</strong></td>
        <td>Co-located with conferences</td>
        <td>Early-stage ideas, position papers, ongoing work. Lower acceptance bar, great for feedback.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Conferences</strong></td>
        <td>6–12 months from submission to proceedings</td>
        <td>The primary venue for mature contributions in AI/ML/Robotics. Top venues: NeurIPS, ICML, ICLR, CVPR, ECCV, ICCV, ICRA, IROS, RSS.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Journals</strong></td>
        <td>1–2+ years from submission</td>
        <td>Comprehensive, extensively reviewed work. Top journals: TPAMI, IJCV, IJRR, Robotics and Autonomous Systems.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>
    For your thesis literature review, focus primarily on top-tier conference papers
    (the last 3–5 years) and journal papers for foundational methods.
  </p>

  <h3>Understanding Conference and Journal Rankings</h3>

  <p>
    Not all venues carry the same weight. Use dedicated ranking resources to assess
    the prestige of a conference or journal before deciding how much to trust its papers:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Conferences</strong> — use the
      <a href="https://scie.lcc.uma.es/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">SCIE Conference Ranking</a>
      to check the tier (A*, A, B, C) of a venue. A* and A conferences (e.g., NeurIPS, CVPR, ICRA)
      represent the gold standard; B venues are still reputable but less selective.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Journals</strong> — use
      <a href="https://www.scimagojr.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">SCImago Journal Rank (SJR)</a>
      to look up a journal's quartile (Q1–Q4) within its subject area. Q1 journals are the most
      prestigious; Q4 journals warrant extra scrutiny.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    That said, venue prestige is a useful heuristic, not a verdict. <strong>The content of a
    paper is always the primary thing to evaluate.</strong> A preprint or a workshop paper can
    contain a genuinely important idea; conversely, even top-tier venues occasionally publish
    flawed work. Read critically regardless of where a paper appeared.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Paper Types ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="paper-types">Types of Papers</h2>

  <p>
    Learning to distinguish what kind of paper you need at any given moment will save you a lot of reading time.
    Here are the main types of research papers you'll encounter:
  </p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Type</th><th>Description</th><th>How to identify it</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Full paper</strong></td>
        <td>The standard research contribution. Presents a problem, method, experiments, and analysis.</td>
        <td>8–16 pages; peer-reviewed at a main conference or journal.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Short paper</strong></td>
        <td>A focused contribution — same rigour, narrower scope.</td>
        <td>4–6 pages; often marked explicitly.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Survey / Review</strong></td>
        <td>Systematically covers an entire research area. Excellent entry point for new topics.</td>
        <td>Titles like "A Survey of…", "Recent Advances in…".</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Preprint</strong></td>
        <td>Not yet peer-reviewed. Fast to share, but treat with appropriate scepticism.</td>
        <td>arXiv ID (e.g., arXiv:2312.12345). Check if a peer-reviewed version exists.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <!-- ── Finding Papers ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="finding">Finding Papers</h2>

  <p>
    Start broad with a survey paper, then narrow to the specific methods most relevant
    to your work.
  </p>

  <h3>Search Engines</h3>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Tool</th><th>Best for</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><a href="https://scholar.google.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Google Scholar</a></td>
        <td>General search; citation counts; "Cited by" to find follow-up work.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><a href="https://arxiv.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">arXiv</a></td>
        <td>The latest preprints in cs.CV, cs.LG, cs.RO. Subscribe to daily digest emails.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><a href="https://www.semanticscholar.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Semantic Scholar</a></td>
        <td>AI-powered related-paper discovery; excellent citation graph.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><a href="https://paperswithcode.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Papers with Code</a></td>
        <td>Find papers that have public implementations; benchmark leaderboards.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><a href="https://openreview.net" target="_blank" rel="noopener">OpenReview</a></td>
        <td>Full peer review history for ICLR, NeurIPS, and others — invaluable for understanding how reviewers think.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><a href="https://www.scopus.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Scopus</a></td>
        <td>A comprehensive research database with a query-based search engine for journal articles. Keyword queries retrieve articles containing those words. Requires a PoliMI account.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>A systematic search workflow</h3>

  <p>
    When entering a new area, use this sequence to build a solid understanding quickly:
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li>Search for a recent <strong>survey paper</strong> on your topic. This gives you vocabulary, landmarks, and an overview of open problems.</li>
    <li>Identify the <strong>5–10 most-cited papers</strong> in the area from the survey's references. These are the foundational methods.</li>
    <li>For each foundational paper, follow its <strong>"Cited by"</strong> chain on Google Scholar to find the latest work that builds on it. Also browse the <strong>conference proceedings</strong> of relevant top-tier venues to catch important papers that might not surface through citation chains.</li>
    <li>Repeat steps 2 and 3 <strong>periodically</strong> as your thesis progresses — the state of the art shifts quickly and staying current is an ongoing habit, not a one-off task.</li>
    <li>Stay updated on <strong>LinkedIn and X (Twitter)</strong> by following prominent researchers, lab accounts, and conference pages. Announcements, code releases, and early discussion of new results surface here before anywhere else.</li>
  </ol>

  <!-- ── Quality ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="quality">Evaluating Paper Quality</h2>

  <p>
    Not all published work is equally rigorous. Before spending significant time on a
    paper, do a quick quality check:
  </p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Signal</th><th>What to check</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Venue</strong></td>
        <td>Is it a top-tier conference (NeurIPS, CVPR, ICML, ICLR, ICRA…)? Use <a href="https://scie.lcc.uma.es/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">SCIE</a> for conferences and <a href="https://www.scimagojr.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">SCImago</a> for journals to check rankings.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Citation count</strong></td>
        <td>Many citations relative to paper age suggest community acceptance. Treat with caution for preprints.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Ablation studies</strong></td>
        <td>Does the paper isolate contributions? A method without ablations may have unexplained gains.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Baselines</strong></td>
        <td>Are the comparisons fair and against strong, contemporary baselines?</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Code availability</strong></td>
        <td>Open-source code strongly suggests the results are reproducible.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Error bars</strong></td>
        <td>Are results reported over multiple runs with standard deviation or confidence intervals?</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <!-- ── Organising Papers ──────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="organising">Organising Papers</h2>

  <p>
    A well-organised library pays dividends at every stage of your thesis — from literature
    review to writing the final draft. The standard tool we recommend is
    <a href="https://www.zotero.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Zotero</strong></a>
    (free, open-source, with excellent browser integration).
  </p>

  <h3>Getting started with Zotero</h3>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Save papers in one click</strong> — install the
      <a href="https://www.zotero.org/download/connectors" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Zotero Connector</a>
      browser extension. When you visit a paper page (Google Scholar, arXiv, ACM DL, etc.) the
      connector detects the metadata and saves the full record — including the PDF — directly to
      your library.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Organise with collections and tags</strong> — create a collection per thesis chapter
      or research theme. Use tags to mark papers by status (e.g., <em>to-read</em>,
      <em>key-paper</em>, <em>cited</em>).
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Annotate PDFs inside Zotero</strong> — highlight passages and add notes directly in
      the built-in PDF reader. All annotations are searchable and attached to the entry.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Export BibTeX</strong> — right-click a collection → <em>Export Collection</em> →
      BibTeX. Paste the resulting <code>.bib</code> file into your LaTeX project and reference
      papers with <code>\cite{}</code>.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Syncing your library with OneDrive via ZotMoov</h3>

  <p>
    By default, Zotero stores PDFs in its own data directory. The
    <a href="https://github.com/wileyyugioh/zotmoov" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>ZotMoov</strong></a>
    plugin lets you automatically move attachments to a folder of your choice — such as your
    PoliMI OneDrive — keeping your PDFs backed up and accessible across devices:
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li>Download and install the ZotMoov <code>.xpi</code> from its GitHub releases page via
      <em>Tools → Add-ons → Install Add-on From File</em> in Zotero.</li>
    <li>In <em>Tools → ZotMoov Preferences</em>, set the destination directory to a folder
      inside your OneDrive (e.g., <code>OneDrive/Zotero/Papers</code>).</li>
    <li>Enable <em>"Automatically move files on add"</em> so every new attachment lands in
      OneDrive immediately.</li>
    <li>Use <em>Tools → ZotMoov → Move All Attachments</em> to migrate your existing library
      in bulk.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    Your PDFs are now synced to OneDrive, while Zotero's metadata and annotations live in the
    free Zotero cloud sync — giving you redundant, cross-device access without paying for
    Zotero storage.
  </p>

  <div class="callout callout-success">
    <svg class="w-5 h-5 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5 text-green-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor"
         stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
